GUANYIN

Sometimes on my way to work,
I'd see you exiting the apartment complex
where the kids hung their bodies out the 5th floor window
and hollered the name of my employer
because that's all they knew of me.

And I must confess, I don't know your name either,
just the sway of your hips,
and your imperial pink wig,
and the sweet child that calls you Mama
and clutches your hand.

“You can tell by the hands—“
my coworker says one day,
because he does not know that I am like you
“—those big, strong hands.”

But what's wrong with big hands?
Do we think their volume is only good for holding
all the hatred and violence
you can squeeze into a tightly bound fist?

Think instead of Guanyin, whose hand is so large
that she can hold the entire world in her palm,
and yet her love for humanity was so boundless
that she had to grow a thousand more
just to reach out to everyone in need.

Think of how much more love and justice
you can hold in the palm of your hand
when you cradle it around your daughter's
compared to these men who make fists
and think they can know us by our hands.
